            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mei Lin was raised not in a city, but in the misty shadow of the Northern California redwoods. Her parents, a woodworker and a botanist, instilled in her a profound connection to the earth, teaching her the names of ferns and the language of the tides. Formal education felt distant and abstract compared to the tangible lessons of the forest floor. Her knowledge wasn't certified by a university, but etched into her by seasons of observation.\n\nIn her twenties, Mei\u2019s passion channeled into fierce activism. She was a front-line defender, chaining herself to ancient trees and organizing blockades against logging companies. The turning point came at 28, after a protracted and bitter fight to save an old-growth grove ended in failure. Watching the bulldozers move in, she felt the futility of pure opposition. A heartbreaking loss, it forged a new, pragmatic path. She realized that to save the environment, she had to learn the language of the people destroying it: business, policy, and compliance.\n\nShe spent the next decade devouring regulatory manuals, building a network, and taking on small, pro-bono consulting jobs. Her lack of a formal degree was an obstacle, but her encyclopedic, real-world knowledge of ecosystems and environmental law was undeniable. She could walk a construction site and identify risks a dozen engineers might miss. This reputation eventually led to her current role as a Senior Environmental Consultant, where she advises corporations on minimizing their ecological impact.\n\nNow at 50, Mei lives a quiet, deliberate life in her Inner Sunset apartment, which doubles as her office. Her mornings start with a walk through Golden Gate Park, a ritual that grounds her before a day of digital blueprints and video calls. Her social circle is small, comprised of a few old friends who understand her journey from protestor to pragmatist. Her hope is not to start a revolution, but to embed real, lasting change from within the system she once fought. She dreams of one day buying a small plot of worn-out land and spending her retirement nursing it back to health, a final, personal act of restoration."
